        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>SENSITIVITY REQUIREMENTS
The primary goal of this proposal is to detect the absorption of the emission of several molecular lines against a background continuum source. We request band 6, because it includes the 1-0 transitions of interest that we think will be populated by the background radiation and absorb its emission. The  background source will be unresolved and we only require a reasonably small
angular resolution of 2".

The background source has a flux of 0.3 mJy at 3mm. Our aim is to reach a 5-sigma limit to detect the absorbing line, assuming a line width of 0.5 km/s. We have estimated that an rms noise of 10 mJy/beam per channel for a spectral resolution of 0.2 km/s is able to give us an integrated opacity of  0.1 for a 0.3 background source, which should be enough to detect the expected lower abundances of the molecular species in the more diffuse gas.

We will use a correlator setup that optimizes the selection of the larger amount of molecular lines observable at a velocity resolution of 0.2 km/s

IMAGING
For this observations we require one individual pointing

CORRELATOR SETUP
We will observe 6 spectral windows in 4 basebands all in the LSB (2 spectral windows in two basebands and one each in the other two basebands), with a spectral resolution of 60 kHz and a 59 MHz bandwidth. We will tune the spectral windows to observe the HCN (1-0) line at 88.63 GHz, the C2H (1-0) line at 87.32 GHz, the HCO+ (1-0) and HOC+ (1-0) lines at 89.18 and 89.49 GHz, respectively; the H13CO+(1-0) and HCO (1-0) lines at 86.7 GHz, and the H13CN (1-0) line at 86.3 GHz

CALIBRATION
We will use our background continuum source QSO J1713-2658 as gain calibrator, because is bright enough to be used as such, and thus the observation will be more efficient.

DATA RATE
The data rate is 13.59 MB/s (&gt; 12 MB/s) but we cannot apply any extra spectral averaging to reduce it because the possible emission absorption detections would be at risk if the lines are too narrow

TIME REQUEST
We estimate that we need 12 minutes on source in order to achieve an rms of 10 mJy/beam per channel, for a total time of 44.04 minutes after adding calibration and overheads.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
