        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>SENSITIVITY REQUIREMENTS
The primary goal of this proposal is to detect the absorption of the emission of several molecular lines against a background continuum source. We request band 6, because it includes the 1-0 transitions of interest that we think will be populated by the background radiation and absorb its emission. The  background source will be unresolved and we only require a reasonably small angular resolution of 2".

The background source has a flux of 0.3 mJy at 3mm. Our aim is to reach a 5-sigma limit to detect the absorbing line, assuming a line width of 0.5 km/s. We have estimated that an rms noise of 10 mJy/beam per channel for a spectral resolution of 0.2 km/s is able to give us an integrated opacity of 0.1 for a 0.3 background source, which should be enough to detect the expected lower abundances of the molecular species in the more diffuse gas.

We will use a correlator setup that optimizes the selection of the larger amount of molecular lines observable at a velocity resolution of 0.2 km/s 

IMAGING
For this observations we require one individual pointing

CORRELATOR SETUP
We will observe 5 spectral windows in 4 basebands (two in the LSB and two in
the uSV). Four of the spectral windows will have a 59 MHz bandwidth with about
61 kHz spectral resolution, and the fifth spectral window, which will be used
for self-calibration will use 2 GHz bandwidth at 31.250 MHz resolution and 
will be tuned at 99 GHz. The  spectral windows will be tuned to observe the
lines CS (2-1) at 97.99 GHz; CN (1-0, 1/2-1/2) and (1-0,3/2-3/2) at 113.17 and
113.51 GHz and the C18O (1-0) line at 109.78 GHz.

CALIBRATION
We will use our background continuum source QSO J1713-2658 as gain calibrator, because is bright enough to be used as such, and thus the observation will be more efficient.

TIME REQUEST
We estimate that we need 12 minutes on source in order to achieve an rms of 10 mJy/beam per channel,for a total of 53.15 min after adding calibration and overheads.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
