    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The chemistry of the diffuse molecular gas in dark clouds is difficult to asses, because most molecular lines are heavily subthermalized and difficult to detect. The measure of the molecular abundances and the physical properties of this translucent gas is becoming more and more important to provide realistical initial conditions to the chemical models that study the evolution of gas from diffuse to dense phases (and star formation) and to model the chemistry of this dark molecular gas. We propose a novel way to better characterize this chemistry by observing a not particularly bright QSO toward a star-foming and a quiescent dark cloud, the Pipe Nebula, and to detect at high spectral resolution the absorption of the emission by key molecular species. Only ALMA can use this new way of probing the properties of the diffuse molecular gas around denser dark molecular cores, which may prove crucial to understand the nature of the dark molecular gas in the Galaxy.</prp:abstract>
